{"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "schema", "document", "Document"], "kwargs": {"metadata": {"source": "pdfs/Population-synthesis-using-incomplete-microsample.pdf", "page_numbers": "[3]", "headings": "['2. Methodology']"}, "page_content": "2. Methodology\nWe used Neves et al. (2022) masking approach to handle missing data. We introduce a new matrix, known as the mask, as input during WGAN-GP training. The mask, Y , represents the training data, X , with a zero representing a missing value and a one representing any non-missing value. Thus, the mask is a binary matrix of the same size as X . The primary distinction from the original WGAN-GP training algorithm lies in multiplying the generator's output by mask Y , which then serves as the input for discriminator D , thereby generating a score for fake samples. Figure 1 provides an illustration of the proposed training method, showcasing the training routine for both the generator and the discriminator.\nFig. 1: Illustration of proposed methodology for WGAN-GP models.", "type": "Document"}}